<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-316-632  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 316 632.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  March 19 1990 v4 n11 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ANSI calls fed Standards Council overkill; proposal is consideredtactic to boost US competitiveness. (the American NationalStandards Institute will challenge the US National Institute ofStandards and Technology plan for strengthening the federal rolein setting standards)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smithmidford, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) hasproposed the establishment of a Standards Council of the USA(SCUSA) to coordinate domestic and international standardsactivities, but the American National Standards Institute (ANSI)believes the plan is unnecessary.andP;  The eight-point NIST plandefines SCUSA's missions, which include encouraging governmentdevelopment and use of standards, providing information to USinterests on standards and related testing and certification,effecting agreements through the Commerce Dept for consistentinternational standards development, providing financialassistance for US representation on international standards groupsand accrediting US standards groups to international bodies.andP;  ANSIintends to protest the SCUSA proposal at NIST hearings in April,1990; but NIST itself is apparently not totally committed to theSCUSA plan.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ANSIStandardsProposalGoals and ObjectivesGovernment AgencyGovernment RegulationUnited States. National Institute of Standards and TechnologyAmerican National Standards Institute.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>